  "prompt": "What is difference between logical memory, physical memory and virtual memory?",
  "response": "Let me explain the differences between logical memory, physical memory, and virtual memory:\n\n1. Physical Memory:\n- Actual hardware memory (RAM) in a computer\n- Directly accessible by the CPU\n- Limited in size\n- Consists of physical storage locations\n- Measured in bytes/megabytes/gigabytes\n- Directly connected to the computer's motherboard\n\n2. Logical Memory:\n- Memory as perceived by a process or program\n- Memory address space used by a program\n- Represents memory from the perspective of a running application\n- Abstraction of memory layout\n- Independent of physical memory allocation\n- Contains code, data, stack, and heap segments\n\n3. Virtual Memory:\n- Memory management technique\n- Provides an abstraction layer between logical and physical memory\n- Allows programs to use memory beyond physical RAM\n- Uses hard disk space as an extension of RAM\n- Enables memory protection and isolation between processes\n- Uses paging and memory mapping techniques\n- Provides:\n  - Memory isolation\n  - Protection\n  - Efficient memory utilization\n  - Larger addressable memory space\n\nKey differences:\n- Physical memory is hardware-based\n- Logical memory is program-perspective\n- Virtual memory is a memory management technique bridging logical and physical memory\n\nExample:\n- Physical Memory: 8 GB RAM\n- Logical Memory: Memory layout of a specific program\n- Virtual Memory: Uses disk space to extend RAM, allowing more memory usage",
